            "answer_text": "Let n = k + 3 Case 1: k = 1 3^4 = 81 and 4^3 = 64 3^4 > 4^3 Case 2: let there be a natural number m, k = m, such that 3^(m + 3) > (m + 3)^3 Prove by induction that when k = m + 1, 3^(m + 4) > (m + 4)^3 From case 2, 3 * 3^(m + 3) > 3 * (m + 3)^3 3^(m + 4) > 3 * (m + 3)^3 But 3 * (m + 3)^3 > (m + 4)^3 if and only if 3 > ((m + 4)/(m + 3))^3 = (1 + 1/(m + 3))^3 1 + 1/(m + 3) <= 1 + 1/4 = 1.25 So (1 + 1/(m + 3))^3 <= (1.25)^3 = 1.953125 < 3 Thus (1 + 1/(m + 3))^3 < 3 3^(m + 4) > 3 * (m + 3)^3 and 3^(m + 3)^3 > (m + 4)^3 means 3^(m + 4)^3 > 3 * (m + 3)^3 > (m + 4)^3, which implies 3^(m + 4)^3 > (m + 4)^3 ",
